ce:section.ce:para:
Recently, doping heteroatoms, especially sulfur, in a carbon framework has been an attractive strategy to enhance the catalytic activity, generate defective states and change the electronic structure of carbon materials [11,12,31]. Many research groups have attempted to synthesize a variety of sulfur doped nanomaterials with distinct physicochemical property [32–34]. However, most of sulfur doped nanomaterials were synthesized using carbon precursor and extra dopant, respectively. In addition, it is hard to guarantee the formation of core doping owing to different structures and reactivity of two separated precursors [22], which could have significant effects in the context of catalysis through engineering of energy levels or enhancing the efficiency of charge transfer reactions [35]. To avoid tedious and uncontrollable doping, herein, we presented a simple strategy that fluorescent S-Ndots with high percentage of the element nitrogen and sulfur have been synthesized using 2-azidothiazole as a single-source precursor. Herein, 2-azidoimidozole served as carbon, nitrogen and sulfur source simultaneously not only improve the effect of doping in a molecular level but also guarantee efficient core doping. As shown in Figs. S1, 2-azidothiazole was synthesized from 2-aminoimidazole, HAc, and NaNO2 in dichloromethane [36], and which was confirmed by 1HNMR and mass spectrum (
                        Fig. S2 and Fig. S3
                        ).

The possible mechanism for the formation of S-Ndots is that generated from decomposition of azido moiety, nitrene, the active intermediate, reacted with double bond of 2-azidothiazole to form tricycle of aziridine moiety, and then self-polymerized [1,2]. Finally, at supersaturation point S-Ndots were synthesized by probable nuclear burst after a ring-opening reaction in water (

                        Scheme 1
                        ). Furthermore, 2-azidothiazole was mixed with methyl acrylate at room temperature for five days in order to confirm the hypothesized mechanism (
                        Fig. S4
                        ). Fortunately, a trapped product of active intermediate of self-polymerization was isolated and proved to be 2-aziridinecarboxylic acid-1-(1H-thiazole-2-yl) methyl ester, which was confirmed by 1HNMR spectrum (
                        Fig. S5
                        ). To highlight the function of 2-azidothiazole, other S doped N-dots were specially synthesized using as a starting material with 2-aminothiazole, which is similar to that of 2-azidoimidazole in molecular structure, also including carbon, nitrogen and sulfur source simultaneously. However, as shown in Table S1, there were much lower content of nitrogen and sulfur using 2-aminothiazole as a starting material compared to 2-azidoimidazole, and the possible reason is that there is no active azido moiety in 2-aminothiazole. Therefore, 2-azidothiazole was chosen as a SSP because azido moiety and double bond are both vital in the structure for synthesizing S-Ndots with excellent optical properties.

The UV–visible absorption and FL spectra of the S-Ndots are shown in 
                        Fig. 2, and the absorption spectrum shows a peak at near 240 nm, attributing to the typical absorption of the π→π * transition [40]. Like other quantum dots, the S-Ndots also show an excitation dependence property under different excitation wavelengths, and this behavior may arise from particles of different size [19,21]. Furthermore, as shown in Fig. S7, the Commission International d′Eclairage (CIE) chromaticity coordinates reveals that the S-Ndots exhibit blue fluorescence. A more interesting thing is that the S-Ndots were made fluorescent patterns through ink-jet printer onto a paper substrate and transferred as a bright blue patterns, which indicated that water-soluble S-Ndots were potential in invisible security ink for creating versatile patterns, information coding and decryption (
                        Fig. S8
                        ). In addition, the S-Ndots showed excellent solubility in water owing to the presence of rich hydrophilic groups (-OH), and which were so stable even within several months without the observation of any precipitation and the FL intensity did not apparently change even under various pH values or high concentrations of NaCl solutions (
                        Fig. S9
                        ).

As stated above, a highly selective dual-mode (colorimetric and fluorometric) sensor based on the S-Ndots for the detection of Hg2+ was proposed. Most of previously reported nanosensors focused on single readout, either fluorometric or colorimetric mode, which may be difficult to meet the requirements of the accuracy and diverse assay [47]. This dual-mode sensing assay provides a promising alternative for more reliable detection because they could offer fluorometric and colorimetric mode simultaneously, thus providing improved accuracy and attractive diversity. In order to demonstrate the analytical performance of the proposed nanosensor in complicated environmental samples, the Hg2+ concentrations in real samples have been determined colorimetrically and fluorometrically with the nanosensor. The practical assay for Hg2+ determination in water sample was explored by using contaminated industrial waste water containing different concentrations of Hg2+. The Hg2+ concentrations determined using a fitting curve match well with the standard concentrations of contaminated industrial waste water with a slight increase (
                        Fig. S11
                        ). Despite potential interference from numerous metal ions and organics existing in industrial waste water, the S-Ndots sensor could still distinguish between contaminated and non-contaminated river water, providing the practical Hg2+ detection in industrial waste water. Recoveries of the known spiked amounts of Hg2+ in real water samples were between 94.0% and 120.0% with RSD below 9.0% (

                        Table 1
                        ). In addition, the sensitivity of this method was comparable to that of the colorimetric methods for Hg2+, and fluorescent and colorimetric methods for the simultaneous detection of Hg2+ in environmental samples (

                        Table 2
                        ).

To evaluate the potential of biological application of the S-Ndots, toxicity studies of the S-Ndots were performed with A549 cells as the model by the standard CCK-8 assay (

                        Fig. 5
                        ). After different concentrations of the S-Ndots solution were incubated with A549 cells for 24 h and 48 h, respectively, they showed no apparent toxicity to the cells even though the S-Ndots concentration was up to 300 μg/mL; thus the S-Ndots showed low toxicity and membrane-permeable. Therefore, the S-Ndots displayed excellent biocompatibility, suggesting the potential application of bioimaging.
